<font color="#FF0000">STOP CONTROLLING</font><br>
<tt>Sun Jul 27 14:09:15 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It would be nice to have a place to go to talk with other COMBAT VETERANS about shared feelings and common ground regarding the war, and not have to contend with some OUTSIDER'S parent/child transaction analysis interjecting a continuous flow of disruptive, critical commentary.<br>
I am not allowed to go to the country club and sit around and discuss topics (any topics) with the membership.  If I have not paid my dues I am not priviledged to fellowship.  It doesn't matter that I was unable or unwilling to pay the price.  The bottom line is that I did not PAY!  I will not stand at the fence and scream at them about how foolish it is to play golf and disrupt their game, or shout criticisms about their swing (when I have never played the game.)<br>
Certainly, it doesn't pay tribute to the members to engage the scoundrel hanging on the fence.  Perhaps it is better to move farther away from the fence.<br><br>
I believe in freedom of speech and freedom from speech.  I believe in freedow of religion which allows me to accept some ideas and reject others.<br><br>
Following the Oklahoma City Bombing, where several Native Americans where among the killed, a place was set aside where families and friends awaiting the results of the rescue efforts could appeal to God in prayer, in their own style.  They called for a Holy Man to minister to them and that person came, bring cedar and Eagle feathers.  Cedar smoke, not unlike Holy Water and other religious symbols of other faiths, is a purifying agent and many believe that the curling rising wafts of smoke help in lifting the prayers toward the Creator.  Wambli Ogleska, the young spotted (immature) Eagle represents a helper, one who ascends to high places... therefore one capable of carrying a plea to a higher place.  An Eagle feather is often used to fan the Cedar smoke.  A nearby group of fundamentalist Christians, exercising their freedom of religion were horrorified by the acts of the pagan &quot;Indians.&quot;  They encircled the small group of grief stricken Native Americans, against their polite wishes, and assailed them with shouted exorcisms and wailing petitions submitted in &quot;Tongues.&quot;  The religious zealots had not lost anyone in the bombing.  Their intent, though honorable, was an intrusion... an unwelcome assertation of their values and ideas.  Their freedom of expression robbed my people of their freedom and rights.  It was a sad event.  The intruders simply wanted God to intervene in behalf of the injured and their expectant loved ones.  Their good intentions (unhampered by a concern for the values of others) created pain and anger.<br>
I do not wish to deprive war protestors of their voice.  I simply choose to avoid their unwelcomed opinions while I seek to dig my brothers from the rubble of social ills.  Part of the process, to me, is the investigation and discovery which occurs along side those who share a common experience, the first-hand exposure to warfare.  I feel that those, without combat experience who wish to observe the exchange should be allowed to do so... as long as their howling protestations do not interfer with the private and scared dialog.<br><br>
&quot;Let not him that girdeth on his harness boast himself as he that putteth it off.&quot;    1 Kings  20:11
